\begin_layout Section
TX Arbitrator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
TX Arbitrator implements following functionality:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Selects TXT Buffer for Transmission based on TXT Buffer priority.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Loads CAN frame metadata from TXT Buffer to registers to be provided for
 CAN Core during transmission.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Loads timestamp from TXT Buffer and compares it with actual value of Timestamp
 input.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Holds index of TXT Buffer from which CAN Core is actually transmitting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset include
LatexCommand input
filename "entity_docs/tx_arbitrator.lyx"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
TX Arbitrator block diagram is shown in Figure TODO.
 TX Arbitrator selects Highest priority TXT Buffer for transmission.
 Only TXT Buffers which are in state 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Ready
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are considered for selection.
 Priority comparison is executed by Priority decoder.
 TX Arbitrator contains a FSM which controls loading of CAN frame metadata
 and Timestamp comparison.
 Selection of highest priority TXT Buffer in TX Arbitrator is executed in
 single cycle by Priority decoder.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Priority decoder
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Priority decoder combinatorially selects index of highest priority TXT Buffer.
 Priority of TXT Buffer is given by SW from Memory registers.
 If TXT Buffer is not in Ready state, it is not considered for selection.
 If two buffers are of equal priority, buffer with lower priority is selected.
 Priority decoder is implemented as comparator tree with 3 levels and it
 is shown in Figure TODO.
 Priority decoder supports 8 input TXT Buffers.
 If number of input TXT Buffers is lower than 8, unused inputs are driven
 to zeroes.
 If no TXT Buffer is in Ready state, priority decoder signals that no TXT
 Buffer is ready and no frame can be transmitted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
TX Arbitrator FSM
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
State transition diagram of TX Arbitrator FSM is shown in Figure TODO.
 Each state of TX Arbitrator FSM which loads data from TXT Buffer RAM lasts
 two clock cycles (there is internal wait state) since TXT Buffer RAM is
 synchronous and it takes one clock cycle to read memory word from this
 RAM.
\end_layout

